<br />
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Well, thìs is LotR, and there is not much skill involved in playing the game, so there`s not much strategy behind this deck... When playing against Moria, play all your companions as you get them, and when you think you`re opponent is about to drop a Nertea, try to lose some companions. If you see your opponent is playing with Moria Scouts, then don`t be afraid to get your Arwen and Legolas killed so he can`t play them for free. You should think about suiciding Legolas when the game nears its end and your opponent has a healthy supply of Goblin Armories, since his archery will have little consequence on the game. Be careful when you choose to play your Servants and when you use Trust Me, because they can save you at the end of the game. Try not to waste them on killing the Cave Troll, but don`t hesitate to use them when it would prevent your opponent from stacking on the swarm, or when it would allow one of your companions to block the Cave Troll twice.<br />
<br />
Against Uruk-Hai:<br />
Playing against Uruk-Hai is always somewhat random nowadays. You could be dominating the game, being at site 8 with a fully-loaded fellowship and no wounds, with your opponent being at site 5 and on the verge of death, and you can move to site 9 and just die. All you got to do against Uruk-Hai is force your opponent to play his boosts early on so that you win all your skirmishes at the end, when it really matters. Also, it helps to draw Gimli`s Helm or Aragorn/Boromir and an Armor early. Sometimes though, there`s nothing you can do.<br />
<br />
Against Nazgul:<br />
Start crying. You shouldn`t win against Nazgul. Between the Gandalf killer, Black Breath, Blade Tip, and Fierce Nazgul that usually always have at least the same strength as your companions, there`s not much to do, especially since you might have to hang on to some of your Servants to protect Gandalf from the Gandalf killer. Thankfully, all the Nazguls got knocked out of Day 2 before they got at me.<br />
<br />
Against Sauron:<br />
I càn`t imagine Sauron would be much of a difficulty. You`ve got Narya to weaken Enduring Evil, Sleep, Caradhras to shatter his conditions, and 8 companions to soak up the damage from Under the Watching Eye and Orc Bowmen. The 3 trackers from his 9th site shouldn`t help him much, because by then you should have Trust Me along with a nice supplement of Servants. There`s a reason Sauron decks rarely make Top 16...<br />
<br />
Against Bill Ferny:<br />
Play intelligently and run like a madman. After the first turn, if you have Sam on the table, do not remove burdens with him in case your opponent plays a common Saruman and tries to frimbazel up your Sam. If he`s fresh, he can live an extra turn, which gets you that much closer to site 9. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php?PHPSESSID=8a35dfea0229fac4dbc2e9b2bd8ea118">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=25417&PHPSESSID=8a35dfea0229fac4dbc2e9b2bd8ea118"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=25417&PHPSESSID=8a35dfea0229fac4dbc2e9b2bd8ea118" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=8a35dfea0229fac4dbc2e9b2bd8ea118">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
